loc: Osaka Castle Park, Chuo-ku, Osaka City, Osaka Prefecture
rmk:
The bird approached but did not show it (probably behind the trees).
After this, no voice was heard and the bird was lost.
The sound quality reminds me of Fairy Pitta (Pitta nympha),
but this voice is higher in frequency and the bird issued single tones
(in contrast to double tones of typical song of Pitta nympha).
If the bird is this species, it is the first record
in Osaka Castle Park.  Could someone help the ID?

Based on sufficient similarity with XC290288 and the presence of a sighting
report of this species in nearby Prefecture on migration,
I give this ID for better exposure.
If you find an even better match, please leave a comment.
